drh added on 2018-04-26 12:45:00:
The following SQL code causes a VDBE fault on the final UPDATE statement,
caused by the use of a register that was previously initialized by SCopy from
another register that subsequently changed.  This is completely harmless in
the example shown, but could cause problems if the value passed was a string or
blob rather than an integer.
CREATE TABLE t1(a INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, b int, c DEFAULT 0)WITHOUT ROWID;
CREATE TABLE record(x TEXT, y TEXT);
CREATE TRIGGER r3 BEFORE UPDATE ON t1 BEGIN
  INSERT INTO record(x,y)
      VALUES('before-update',printf('%d,%d,%d/%d,%d,%d',
                    old.a,old.b,old.c,new.a,new.b,new.c));
END;
INSERT INTO t1(a,b) VALUES(1,2);
UPDATE t1 SET c=a WHERE a=1;
The problem manifests as an assertion fault here:
/artifact/066a4e1de2ed83e2?ln=2813.
Bisecting shows this problem began with the optimization at check-in
[871e091df651b2275a672c] on 2015-10-15 which was first released in
version 3.10.0 on 2016-01-06.  The problem was detected during internal
testing (specifically during AFL testing of the new UPSERT capability
to be added for 3.24.0) and has never been seen in the wild.
